                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The relavence of my opinion is to show why, despite knowing that whatever I offer up for consideration will immediately be twisted, I subject myself to a conversation or a debate or whatever you might wish to call this.  Too many people are willing to get away from the basic fundamentals of right and wrong.  Nobody wants to "get involved" anymore. 
<br />

<br />
What Hussein was doing to his country, his people, his neighboring countries was simply wrong.   Wrongs should be stopped and, if at all possible, righted.  That is the fundamental issue here.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I'd like to dispell the rumor that all the citizens were all being slaughtered in massive amounts. That didn't happen in Iraq. Yes some were, but not to the extent you suggest. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Dispell the rumor?  I'm sorry...but the media has been regularly reporting on the findings of mass graves for months now.  Two days ago another large mass grave was found and the bodies removed.  The news report listed the amount of bodies found in that grave (which I don't remember offhand) and then reported that this number brought the total number of bodies found in mass graves to over 300,000.  I know that the media often makes mistakes in it's reporting...but I find it hard to believe that made a mistake this HUGE.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I don't recall ever saying I was scared of Iraq. You assume when I talk about my "brothers, uncles, and friends", I'm talking about civilians. The people I'm talking about are military personel that actually get sent over to fight.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Please don't talk to me about family and friends in danger.  One member of my family has been killed there and another good friend is at this very moment critically injured and fighting for his life.  I received a letter from my now dead family member shortly before I learned of his death.  His letter scared me to death because he related to me that he was having "bad feelings" about his chances of survival.  His fear wasn't directed at being killed by Iraqi's per se.  You see, he was in the army and in the last month had been spending a great deal of time moving trucks and heavy equipment around the country to be used in the reconstruction effort.  His fear was generated from he called "piss poor road sweeps by the Army...when they do them at all".  He knew that several had already died to roadside bombs and he felt strongly that if the Army would sweep the roads properly before a convoy moved through, much, if not all, of these casualties could be avoided.  His bad feelings proved true...he was killed by a roadside bomb.  In his letters, he often wrote about how surprised he was by the people in Iraq.  Before his deployment, he was fearful that the people there would hate him for being an American.  Hate him for being in there country.  The surprise he found was that everywhere he went where he had contact with civilians, they thanked him for coming to Iraq.  They didn't care WHY he was there...they were just very happy that "the Americans came."
<br />

<br />
One of the last lines in his last letter was about how tired he was of people constantly questioning the reasons behind the war.  He said that everybody had questions...but when he saw how the Iraqi people reacted to his presence he said this:  " Man, I am sick as hell of all the crap going on about why are we doing this, what gives us the right to be here blah blah blah.  I talked to an old man today that I was trying to buy a jacket from.  He barely spoke english.  He wouldn't take my money.  He said he owed me the jacket for coming to his country to save him and his family.  I swear to christ I almost cried when he said it right in front of the Sargeant Major.  That ( he underscored "that" twice) is why we're here man and don't you ever let anyone tell you otherwise."
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">To change Iraq, I simply would prefere a more diplomatic way.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
If you read my earlier posts, I said the same thing.  I certainly would have preferred a peaceful resolution rather than a military one.  I remember a 12 year gap from the end of the Gulf War to the beginning of the current conflict that was all diplomacy.  It didn't work.  
<br />

<br />
So, if you have an answer to my question...command...whatever you want to label it...please tell me.  I want to know.  My family has shed it's blood over this...and if it could have been prevented while still accomplishing what obviously needed doing...I think I have the right to ask for the answer.
<br />

<br />
So, you see, I really don't see where my "personal opinions" have been challenged.  What I have seen is the casual dismissal of facts because you don't like the picture they paint.  The chemical weapons, the weapon inspection reports, the refusal to abide by U.N. resolutions by Hussein, and you even deny a 300,000 person body count at a whim...because it doesn't paint the picture you want to see.  If I gave you a million facts, I have no doubt you would find a way to dismiss them all.
<br />

<br />
By the way, I haven't be playing.  I'm as serious as a heartattack.  Read the sig.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Master Mesmor Izer
<br />
65 Enchanter
<br />
Disciple of the Night
