                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I'm going to deal with Mesmor's post, because it's so full of disinformation, and the information it contains is harmful. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Mesmor wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Iraq....my god where to start?  Violation of 17 U.N. Resolutions that were a condition of their surrender after they were forced out of Kuwait.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Firstly can you list the 17 resolutions that they violated? The UN decided that Iraq was NOT in violation of these resolutions, that's why they didn't take action against Iraq, remember?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">State Sponsored RAPE rooms where men were forced to watch as their wives, sisters, daughters, mothers were raped repeatedly, tortured, and killed.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I've found no evidence of this, can you link a site?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">State Sponsored genocide....hundreds upon hundreds of mass graves have already been found.  Only time will tell how many more graves are yet to be discovered.  Recently, a mass grave with over a thousand bodies was reportedly discovered and opened.  The corpses still had the blind folds over their eyes.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This is false. To date only 40 mass graves have been discovered, the largest so far having less then 1000 bodies in it, although suspected of having as many as 3115 but that hasn't been confirmed.  Many countries including the US use captital punishment as a means of discipline, and no evidence of why these people were killed and buried this way have come forth yet. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Repeated use of weapons of mass destruction.  Some folks forget that a WMD doesn't always create a mushroom cloud.  Countless attacks upon the Kurds have been documented where there is ample evidence that chemical weapons were used on civilians.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This is the biggest myth. Weapons of mass destruction have NOT been found in Iraq. There is still no evidence that Iraq had or used such weapons.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Perhaps just these few reasons aren't enough for some folks to believe that going to war with Iraq was not only warranted, but required.  Frankly, for me, just these reasons ALONE are more than sufficient.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This is true. Most Americans support  the war because of these beliefs, particularly the myth of weapons of mass destruction, but they are still false. Weapons of mass destruction have not been found in Iraq. There is still no evidence that weapons of mass destruction were being planned. They do know the Iraq had the ability to make such weapons though, which is the key point imo.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I am an American.  Despite it's flaws, I believe that it is the greatest country on the face of the planet.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This is false. Canada is the greatest nation on earth, just for inventing Poutine.... mmmmmm. You guys aren't bad neighbors though, besides all the guns! 
<br />

<br />
On a more serious note - democracies are pretty good. They tend to average out the damage you can do because when you get a good president you keep him, when you get a bad one you can get rid of him without much of a fuss. I believe Bush is a good executor, give him a task and he'll do his best to see it through. What does he lack? Vision and the ability to make good decisions. 
<br />

<br />
I'd give him a passing grade, but he's not the same quality I've come to expect from Americans in the last couple hundred years. At least he's a great capitalist, the economy is going well again, but unfortunately that expertise isn't doing him much good in Iraq where he needs to be focusing less on the economic structure and attracting money to establishing sound founding principles with the Iraq people. His main mistake came by allowing himself to be caught up in the post 9/11 hysteria which led to the war in Iraq, something very understandable since the majority of Americans felt the same way. Unfortunately, this is one of the issues where I believe the majority should not rule. 
<br />

<br />
That being said, the potential threat from many of the unstable elements in that region and Iraq's close relationship with North Korea are why I feel it was invaded. It made a simple safe target to take out since for the last 10 years they have been so cut off as to not be a threat to anyone making it the ideal place to conquer. 
<br />

<br />
Why not some of these other targets? Largely because they have better relationships with the UN then Iraq or North Korea, and the US has had a large millitary presence in Korea for a long time, it's more stable and isolated then Iraq was. 
<br />

<br />
It isn't sufficient for a country to mistreat it's own citizens to warrent invasion, but rather they they are uncooperative internationally, which is mainly true of Iraq and North Korea, and not true of places like India or China where what many of us would consider atrocities take place. Even Iran has a better relationship with the UN then these countries, and it's also why the US has consistent backed Isreal despite it's instability. That's my take on it anyway. It's not really about being a moral country, it's about a basic level of diplomacy that existing so that we know they aren't going to wipe us all out.
<br />

<br />
I don't think we need to try and justify the invasion by suggesting we had some moral high ground to stand on, or a noble cause to back - this war gives us neither. Instead it was a practical work to prevent someone who'd been uncooperative and hostile from continuing to be so which establishing power and stability in a part of the world where this sort of behaviour seems to be most prominent. If you were a teacher, and someone was being anti-social and threatening other kids, you'd put his desk right next to yours and keep him under stern watch all the time. Especially after giving him 10 years to try and work it out on his own. The majority of Iraqi's feel that they will be better off because of the US invasion in the long term, that's a good enough OK for me to want to see it through till they're back on their feet.  <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" /></span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.style.org/unladenswallow/" target="_blank" class="postlink">What IS the flight velocity of an unlaiden swallow?</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
