                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I think that, at this time, with the information I have, war isn't required to deal with the situation in Iran.  There is enough information about Iran to warrant watching them like a hawk.
<br />

<br />
Iran has concealed a large amount of information about their nuclear program and as each month goes by we learn more and more.  If a country wants to develope nuclear power simply as a means of producing energy I really don't have an issue with it.  However, traces of weapons grade material have been found in Iran.  The Iranian government claims that this weapon grade material found it's way into Iran on equipment it purchased from another country that it is using to build a nuclear facility with peaceful purposes.  The claim itself is suspect in my opinion.  What are they buying here?  USED nuclear equipment?  If the equip is in fact used, it seems to me that the seller would have made every effort to completely sterilzed the equipment before transit to a foreign country.  A couple of obvious reasons exist as to why the equipment would be been cleansed of all nuclear material.  The first, obviously, is safety from the radioactive material.  The second, because it would make it that much more difficult to trace the transit of the equipment from point of origin to point of destination.  
<br />

<br />
Here lies my next area of concern with the claim of Iran.  The plants are to be used for peaceful purposes.  Weapons grade material has been found.  Iran claims that basically it came from the country they purchased the equipment from, which would indicate the equipment had at least at one time been used to produce weapons grade material....and they won't tell anyone WHO they bought the equipment from.  Don't forget, they actively tried to conceal as much of their program as possible.
<br />

<br />
Why conceal a peaceful project.  It would certainly be much easier to simply say "hey...we're gonna build some nuclear power plants so we can have some cheap energy.  Come check it out so you don't have to be nervous about us building nuclear weapons."  Frankly, that's what I would have done.  If traces of weapons grade material were found on the equipment, and I was innocent of having produced it, I'd give up the seller of the equipment damned fast.  Because I would have nothing to hide.
<br />

<br />
It smells more and more like Iran is playing the same shell game that Iraq played with the weapons inspection teams.  They concede just enough to placate without being completely forthright and honest.
<br />

<br />
If I had to predict what would come of this "peaceful" power plant, I would say that unless the Iranian government becomes completely cooperative and allows the program to be monitered closely, those power plants will never go online.  They will, most likely, be destroyed by Isreal.
<br />

<br />
Iraq and Iran are two completely different countries.  One was run by a brutal dictator, the other is run by a group of Mullahs.  I would not be at all surprised to learn that the government of Iran was equally as brutal as that of Iraq.  Call it a gut feeling if you like.  I think that the diplomatic process still has some value with Iran.  In order for it to work however, Iran has to be willing to cooperate.  If that is accomplished, I see no need for war with Iran.  Even now, while Iran is NOT coopertative, I don't see a need for war with Iran.  However, this does not preclude attacks on terrorist organizations within the borders of Iran.  I believe that Iran should be given an opportunity to get a grip on those organizations first.  If they drag their feet, completely turn a blind eye to the situation or are caught aiding those organizations...then I have no problem with any other country doing it for them.
<br />

<br />
The political climate inside Iran appears to be right for regime change from within.  The younger portion of the population in particular seems to be growing more and more unhappy with the way the country is being ran.  The various problems with Iran can be solved peacefully.  I hope that the Iranian government, or the citizens of Iran, see to it that those opportunities are not wasted as they were in Iraq.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Going back in time is a luxury for arm chair politicians.  Knowing what I know now...today...there is no way I could have supported EITHER of those two countries.  Obviously, there is no easy answer to this question of yours.  You and I have the luxury of hindsight to guide our answers...the people that had to make those decisions decades ago did not have that luxury.   I have no idea what information they had on hand that they used to base their decisions on.  For all I know, they were trapped between choosing between the lesser of two evils.  I have been in a few situations like that in my life...you are damned if you go left and you are damned if you go right.  It's a miserable feeling to choose between the lesser of two evils.  
<br />

<br />

<br />
My first instinct when dealing with two countries that are warring with each other, unless one of them is an ally of the United States, is to let them slug it out between themselves.  So long as their conflict doesn't produce a risk the the interests, safety, or security of another innocent nation...I have no issue with staying out of it.  Perhaps THAT is what should have been done during the Iran/Iraq wars.  Maybe natural selection would have prevented the necessity of the war being fought today.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Master Mesmor Izer
<br />
65 Enchanter
<br />
Disciple of the Night
