Where you posted it from has nothing to do as to whether or not it is commentary. Its whats in the article that makes it commentary. Since you don't know the difference between commentary and data, allow me to provide an example:
<br />

<br />
   Second hand smoke has been shown repeatedly to be as dangerous, or more dangerous than firsthand smoke according to a study by &lt;some organization&gt;. In the study, it was found that there is a 35% greater likely hood that the breathers of secondhand smoke will develop smoking related diseases. Public restaurants should shun smoking due to its harmful nature.  
<br />

<br />
( Btw, I made up the stats for sake of the example)
<br />

<br />
In the above example the only "fact(s)" are the first 2 sentences. The commentary is the extension off those facts.
<br />

<br />
In your examples they perdict, guess, etc a lot about what things were, but the fact's don't always lead to the conclusion they suggest.
<br />

<br />
Hard data would be something like a video, which is why I asked for it.  
