No, I'm not saying its all a hoax. I think the justifications for the war are shady. Thats my opinion, however. That isn't what I would like you to adapt. What I would like you to come away with is an understanding for the other side. Even though you might feel what i say is just simple non-sence, you shouldn't apply ailments to it, like the original poster did. Allow me to give an example.
<br />

<br />
Lets say person A believes in Evolution, and person B believes in creationism. Both sides are pretty sure their side is right, and if both are well informed about it, could probably debate for hours and never really be able to reach a conclusive "right" answer. They can, however, walk away respecting one anothers ideas. Your philosophy might be different than mine, but that doesn't mean we have to act hostile toward one another.
<br />

<br />
Allow me to give another example that has the same parelle, but doesn't involve any "issue". Take two cultures. American and Arab. The way they speak when in conversation is very different. Americans stand a few feet back , careful not to invade the "comfort zone", whereas Arabs tend to speak much closer face to face. If someone doesn't understand the other culture, they are likely to take offence to the way they are being spoken too. An american speaking to an arab might feel the arab is being rude and "in his face" whereas the arab may feel the american is being "aloof and uncaring". When you understand its a cultural difference, you can get along a lot easier. 
<br />

<br />
